{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646636","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646636"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:33:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:33:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18196"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18196","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18196"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.84,0.03,0,0.1,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10910"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79343"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10910"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18196"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64665"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"7302"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25364"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25365"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79343","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79343"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESpina bifida is a developmental condition affecting the vertebral column. The occulta variant is characterised by incomplete fusion of vertebral neural arches without involvement of neural tissue.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes spina bifida occulta?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A developmental defect present at birth","A degenerative condition of the thoracic spine","A disorder causing neurological symptoms","A defect with visible skin changes","A condition requiring surgical correction"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA developmental defect present at birth\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes spina bifida occulta, as it results from incomplete fusion of the vertebral neural arches during embryonic development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA degenerative condition of the thoracic spine\u003C/strong\u003E - Spina bifida occulta is developmental, not degenerative, and typically affects the lumbosacral region\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA disorder causing neurological symptoms\u003C/strong\u003E - The condition is typically asymptomatic\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA defect with visible skin changes\u003C/strong\u003E - Most cases have no visible external signs\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA condition requiring surgical correction\u003C/strong\u003E - As it is typically asymptomatic, surgical intervention is not usually required\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe condition is often discovered incidentally during imaging studies performed for unrelated reasons. It most commonly affects the fifth lumbar (L5) or first sacral (S1) vertebrae.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Spina bifida occulta is a congenital condition where the neural arches of the vertebrae fail to fuse completely during development.","Spina bifida occulta most commonly affects the fifth lumbar (L5) or first sacral (S1) vertebrae.","Unlike other forms of spina bifida, the occulta variant is typically asymptomatic and discovered incidentally on imaging."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Henson B, Kadiyala B, Edens MA. Anatomy, Back, Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537074/","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Rockwood, C. A., Wirth, M. A., \u0026 Fehringer, E. V. (2016). Rockwood and Matsen\u0027s The Shoulder E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","DeSai C, Reddy V, Agarwal A. Anatomy, Back, Vertebral Column. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK525969/","Brea CM, Munakomi S. Spina Bifida. 2023 Aug 13. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32644691."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64665"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18196"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64665","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64665"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T10:14:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T10:15:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10910"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79343"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":